Next: Build a simple login + profile screen

Most apps start with Authentication + Cloud Firestore. Below is a streamlined, working flow you can drop into an Activity.

1. Set up Authentication (email/password)

In Firebase Console → Authentication → Sign-in method, enable Email/Password.

```kotlin
// In your sign-up Activity
val auth = Firebase.auth

fun signUp(email: String, password: String) {
    auth.createUserWithEmailAndPassword(email, password)
        .addOnCompleteListener(this) { task ->
            if (task.isSuccessful) {
                // Sign-up success, user is signed in automatically
                val user = auth.currentUser
                saveUserToFirestore(user) // step 2
                startActivity(Intent(this, HomeActivity::class.java))
                finish()
            } else {
                Toast.makeText(this, "Sign-up failed: ${task.exception?.message}", Toast.LENGTH_SHORT).show()
            }
        }
}
```

2. Save extra user data to Firestore

```kotlin
fun saveUserToFirestore(user: FirebaseUser?) {
    user ?: return
    val db = Firebase.firestore
    val userData = hashMapOf(
        "uid" to user.uid,
        "email" to user.email,
        "displayName" to "",
        "createdAt" to FieldValue.serverTimestamp()
    )
    db.collection("users").document(user.uid)
        .set(userData)
        .addOnSuccessListener { Log.d(TAG, "User profile saved") }
        .addOnFailureListener { e -> Log.w(TAG, "Error saving user", e) }
}
```

3. Read data in another screen (e.g., profile)

```kotlin
val db = Firebase.firestore
val currentUser = Firebase.auth.currentUser
currentUser?.let { user ->
    db.collection("users").document(user.uid)
        .get()
        .addOnSuccessListener { document ->
            if (document.exists()) {
                val displayName = document.getString("displayName") ?: "No name"
                binding.textName.text = displayName
            }
        }
}
```

---

Next: Add real-time listening with Coroutines & Flow (modern Kotlin)

Instead of one-time get(), use a snapshot listener that emits updates. With the -ktx extensions, you can use Flow:

```kotlin
// Firestore extension function (in a repository)
fun observeUser(uid: String) = flow {
    val docRef = Firebase.firestore.collection("users").document(uid)
    val listener = docRef.addSnapshotListener { snapshot, e ->
        if (e != null) { close(e); return@addSnapshotListener }
        if (snapshot != null && snapshot.exists()) {
            trySend(snapshot)
        }
    }
    awaitClose { listener.remove() }
}

// In ViewModel
val userFlow = repository.observeUser(uid)
    .map { doc -> doc.toObject(User::class.java) }
    .stateIn(viewModelScope, SharingStarted.WhileSubscribed(5000), null)
```

---

Next: Secure your data with Firestore rules

Without security rules, your database is open. In Firebase Console → Firestore → Rules, start with something like:

```
rules_version = '2';
service cloud.firestore {
  match /databases/{database}/documents {
    match /users/{userId} {
      allow read, write: if request.auth != null && request.auth.uid == userId;
    }
  }
}
```

This ensures a user can only read/write their own document.

