Firebase management typically refers to all the tasks around administering a Firebase project itself (as opposed to writing app code). Below is a breakdown of what that includes and the tools you use.

---

What “Firebase management” covers

Area What it means
Project creation & settings Creating projects, naming, assigning billing account, setting data location.
App registration & configuration Adding Android/iOS/Web apps, downloading config files, registering SHA-1 fingerprints.
Service enabling/disabling Turning on/off individual Firebase services (Auth, Firestore, Storage, etc.).
Team & permissions Adding project members, setting IAM roles (Owner, Editor, Viewer, custom).
Billing & quotas Managing billing, monitoring usage, upgrading plans (Spark → Blaze).
Security & rules Firestore/Storage security rules, Authentication sign-in methods, API key restrictions.
Monitoring & analytics Dashboard, Crashlytics, Performance, Cloud Logging.

---

Primary tools for management

1. Firebase Console (web UI)

The most common way: console.firebase.google.com

· Visual overview, analytics, user management.
· Rule editors, config file download, test lab, etc.
· Good for one-off tasks and quick checks.

2. Firebase CLI (command-line tool)

Install with:

```bash
npm install -g firebase-tools
```

Then login:

```bash
