Here’s a balanced look at the drawbacks you should consider before betting your project on Firebase.

---

Arguments against Firebase (management & platform)

1. Vendor lock-in is real

Firebase provides proprietary APIs and SDKs. Your app becomes tightly coupled to Firebase services (Firestore, Authentication, Cloud Functions).
Impact: Migrating away later is painful — you’d need to rewrite data access layers, authentication flows, and possibly restructure your database schema.

2. Cost at scale can surprise you

The free Spark plan is generous, but once you move to the Blaze plan (required for many features like Cloud Functions, Node.js 10+, etc.), costs can escalate quickly.

· Firestore charges per read/write/delete, not just bandwidth.
· A poorly optimised query or infinite loop in a listener can cause a massive bill.
· No built-in hard cap; you must set budget alerts manually.

3. Limited querying & database constraints

Firestore is great for simple queries but lacks:

· Full-text search (you need a third-party like Algolia or Typesense).
· JOINs or complex relational operations.
· Aggregation queries (count, sum) are limited; you often need distributed counters or Cloud Functions.
· Indexes must be manually managed; missing indexes cause errors.

4. No on-premises or offline development

Everything runs on Google’s infrastructure. There’s no self-hosted version of Firestore or Firebase Auth. Local emulators exist but aren’t identical to production. You cannot run a private instance of Firebase inside your own data centre, which may be a deal-breaker for compliance.

5. Security rules are powerful but complex

Writing, testing, and maintaining Firestore/Storage rules can become messy for large projects. They’re a DSL, not a traditional programming language.

· Debugging rules is hard.
· Complex role-based access often forces you to duplicate logic in Cloud Functions.
· A tiny mistake can expose all user data.

6. Multi-tenancy is limited

If you’re building a SaaS that needs separate databases per client, Firebase doesn’t natively support that. You either:

· Use a single project and partition with custom claims (complex, noisy neighbours).
· Create a separate Firebase project per tenant, which becomes an operational nightmare.

7. Admin SDK & backend only

The Firebase Admin SDK runs on servers, not in the client. While this is correct design, some teams underestimate the amount of Cloud Functions or backend logic they’ll need for things like:

· Data validation beyond security rules.
· Sensitive operations (payment processing).
· Scheduled tasks.
  This adds a non-trivial layer of complexity and cost.

8. Data migration is difficult

Exporting large Firestore datasets is slow and expensive. You can’t easily run a SQL query against your production data. Moving to another database later often requires a long-running export job and custom transformation scripts.

9. Support & service deprecation

Google has deprecated Firebase services before (e.g., Firebase Invites, Firebase Job Dispatcher, Dynamic Links partially deprecated). Critical updates can break your app if you don’t stay current. Official support is limited unless you buy a Google Cloud Support package.

---

When Firebase might still be the right choice

Despite those drawbacks, Firebase excels for:

· Prototyping and MVPs.
· Small to medium-sized apps with simple data models.
· Teams that want to avoid server management entirely.
· Real-time collaboration features (Firestore + Realtime Database).

---

Alternatives to compare against

· Supabase (open-source Firebase alternative, PostgreSQL-based).
· Appwrite (self-hosted or cloud, more flexible).
· Backendless (visual, better data relationships).
· AWS Amplify (larger ecosystem, steeper learning curve).

