· “Many data” → handling large amounts of data / many documents in Firestore or Realtime Database.
· “URL” → managing URLs (Dynamic Links, deep links, or simply storing URLs in the database).

I’ll cover both in a practical way, building on the Firebase knowledge we’ve already discussed.

---

1. Handling “many data” (large datasets) in Firebase

Querying & reading many documents efficiently

Firestore (and Realtime Database) are designed to scale, but you must be careful with reads, costs, and performance.

· Pagination is mandatory
    Don’t fetch all documents at once. Use limit() + startAfter() / endBefore() cursor-based pagination.
  ```kotlin
  val first = db.collection("items")
      .orderBy("createdAt")
      .limit(25)
  
  first.get().addOnSuccessListener { snapshot ->
      // Show first page
      val lastVisible = snapshot.documents.lastOrNull()
      // Next page:
      val next = db.collection("items")
          .orderBy("createdAt")
          .startAfter(lastVisible)
          .limit(25)
  }
  ```
· Realtime updates on large collections
    Be cautious with snapshot listeners on huge collections; every change triggers a read of matching documents. Use specific queries and limits.
· Aggregations (count, sum)
    Firestore has no built-in COUNT or SUM queries. Solutions:
  · Use distributed counters (document fields you increment atomically).
  · Run a Cloud Function that listens for changes and updates an aggregation document.
  · For simple counts, now you can use the count() function in the client SDK (recent addition), which gives a cheaper count of matching documents without reading them all.
· Data modeling for scale
    In Realtime Database, structure data flat and avoid deep nesting. In Firestore, use subcollections wisely. A document can have up to ~1 MB, so don’t store enormous arrays that could exceed that. Distribute data across multiple documents.
· Cost control with many documents
    Firestore charges per read/write/delete. With millions of documents, a full collection scan is expensive. Always build composite indexes and filter on indexed fields to avoid touching many documents.
· Exporting/importing many data
    Use the firestore export and import commands via Firebase CLI or Cloud Console. For huge datasets, export to a Cloud Storage bucket and process with Dataflow or a Cloud Function.

---

2. URLs in Firebase: Dynamic Links, Deep Links, and storing URLs

a) Firebase Dynamic Links (soon deprecated, but still used)

Dynamic Links survived the install process and worked across platforms. However, Firebase has deprecated Dynamic Links in favor of App Links (Android) / Universal Links (iOS) and Custom Deep Links.

· Current recommendation: Use Android App Links + Firebase Hosting or Cloud Functions to create redirect behaviour. No more Firebase Dynamic Links for new projects.
· If you’re still using them, you manage them in the Firebase Console under “Dynamic Links”. But start migrating.

b) Storing URLs in Firestore/Realtime Database

Simple: just save a string field.

```kotlin
data class Profile(
    val website: String = "https://example.com"
)
```

Or an array of URLs:

```kotlin
val urls = listOf("https://...", "https://...")
db.collection("users").document(uid).update("photoUrls", urls)
```

Validation: Security rules can use string() and .matches() to enforce URL format.

c) Generating short URLs via Firebase

You can use the Firebase Dynamic Links API (legacy) or Google’s URL Shortener. But Firebase itself doesn’t offer a standalone URL shortener. Consider using Cloud Functions to generate a shortened link if needed.

d) Handling URL-based push notifications (FCM)

You can include a URL in a notification payload. When the user taps the notification, your app receives the deep link and navigates.

```kotlin
intent.data // contains the URL
```

---

Connection to your previous “Against” concerns

· Many data: “Vendor lock-in” and “cost at scale” are real here. Large Firestore datasets are expensive and hard to move. Design your data model to avoid over-reading.
· URLs: If you rely on Firebase Dynamic Links, its deprecation is an example of service retirement risk. Always decouple deep-link logic from a proprietary service.

