1. Firebase Security & Rules

Goal: Make sure only the right people can read/write your data, and your backend isn’t an open door.

Firestore rules (essential pattern)

```
rules_version = '2';
service cloud.firestore {
  match /databases/{database}/documents {

    // Users can read/write only their own profile
    match /users/{userId} {
      allow read, write: if request.auth != null && request.auth.uid == userId;
    }

    // Only admins can write to the "config" collection
    match /config/{doc} {
      allow read: if true;
      allow write: if request.auth.token.admin == true;  // custom claim
    }
  }
}
```

· Use custom claims for roles (admin, moderator). Set them via Admin SDK.
· Test rules with the built‑in Rules Playground in the Firebase Console.
· Storage rules follow a similar pattern — tie access to auth and file metadata.

Key principle

Always start with deny all, then open selectively. Never rely on client code to hide data.

