4. Performance & cost optimization

Avoid a surprise $30,000 bill. Here’s how:

Issue Solution
Many small reads Batch reads (getAll), cache aggressively with source: cache first.
Real-time listeners on large collections Use limit(), paginate, and unsubscribe in onStop().
Missing indexes Monitor FAILED_PRECONDITION errors; create composite indexes ahead of time.
Expensive aggregations Distributed counters, Cloud Function aggregations, Firestore count() (new).
Large documents Split sub‑objects into subcollections. Keep documents < 100 KiB.
Offline persistence Disable it if you don’t need it – reduces local storage and syncing overhead.
Crashlytics logging Use non‑fatal reporting to catch issues that aren’t crashes but affect experience.

Set budget alerts in Google Cloud Console and use Firebase monitoring dashboards.

---

5. Realtime Database vs Firestore

You might use both, but here’s how they differ:

Feature Realtime Database Cloud Firestore
Data model Single JSON tree Collections & documents
Querying Limited (only one filter/sort) Powerful compound queries, indexing
Scalability Zonal, limited to ~200k concurrent connections (scales up but with sharding tricks) Global, automatic scaling
Pricing Bandwidth + storage Number of reads/writes/deletes + storage
Real-time Very low latency updates Slightly higher latency, but still real-time
Use when… Simpler data, frequent small state sync (like chat presence), very low latency Complex queries, structured data, need offline sync with advanced indexing

Hybrid approach: Use Firestore for user profiles/feeds, Realtime Database for real‑time collaboration or presence.

---

6. Testing & emulator suite

Don’t test against production. Firebase Emulator Suite gives you local versions of:

· Firestore, Realtime Database
· Auth
· Cloud Functions
· Storage
· Pub/Sub (for scheduled functions)

Quick start

```bash
firebase init emulators
firebase emulators:start
```

In your Android code, point to the emulator (10.0.2.2 is the host machine from the emulator):

```kotlin
Firebase.firestore.useEmulator("10.0.2.2", 8080)
Firebase.auth.useEmulator("10.0.2.2", 9099)
```

· Write integration tests with the emulator; data is wiped between runs.
· Validate security rules offline with firebase emulators:exec.

